description.plain:
Taymor Travon McIntyre (born June 16, 2000), professionally known as Tay-K, is an American rapper and songwriter originating from Arlington, Texas.

Tay-K started his rap career as part of the rap group Daytona Boyz alongside rappers PiMPYZ and Santana Sage in 2014. The group released their first track “Drift” on SoundCloud in December 2014. The group released a series of songs, barely getting attention as they performed at various parties attempting to create a presence in the local rap scene. Tay-K began to get nationwide attention due to his conflicts with the law.

On July 26, 2016, Tay-K and six other people were arrested on murder charges due to a home invasion gone wrong. The juvenile rapper was placed under house arrest. Eventually, Tay-K decided to flee the law. Before cutting off his ankle monitor and going on the run, Tay-K took to Twitter and tweeted the following:

fuck dis house arrest shit fuck 12 they gn hav 2 catch me on hood

Tay-K made his way to Elizabeth, New Jersey where he recorded his hit song “The Race”. On June 30, 2017, he was captured by the U.S Marshal Service in New Jersey. On July 23, 2019, Tay-K was sentenced to 55 years in prison. He will not be eligible for parole until he serves at least half of his sentence.

Since his arrest, his management team still continued to release tracks such as “The Race (Remix)” assisted by fellow artists 21 Savage and Young Nudy, “Hard” featuring No Jumper and BlocBoy JB, and “After You”.

songs.title: The Race

description.plain:
Taymor McIntyre, or “Tay-K”, is an Arlington, Texas rapper who became wanted for capital murder at the age of just 16.

In July 2016, Tay-K was involved in a home invasion in Mansfield, Texas, that resulted in the death of 21-year-old Ethan Walker. He was placed on house arrest, but cut off his ankle monitor and fled to New Jersey where he was caught by US Marshalls. He is currently waiting to be extradited back to Texas to be tried on charges of capital murder. It’s thought that he fled Texas because prosecutors were looking to try the then-16-year-old as an adult, making him eligible for the death penalty. Although the capital murder charge, and its mandatory 40-year prison sentence, did not stand up, Tay-K was sentenced to 55 years behind bars on 19 July 2019. The lyrical content of “The Race” was used as evidence to convict him.

The song is called “The Race” because he recorded it while being on the run from the feds. He began to gain popularity on the day of his arrest by strategically releasing “The Race.”

songs.title: M.... She Wrote

description.plain: Originally “Murder She Wrote” on Tay-K’s SoundCloud, “M…. She Wrote” features production from Rob $urreal and appears on Tay-K’s mixtape #SantanaWorld. Throughout the song, Tay-K tells various stories about people who tried to test his gangster, women he’s had sex with, and more. The song’s title was censored by his record label, 88 classic  due to Tay-K actually being tried for capital murder and the title potentially hurting his odds of beating the case.

description.plain:
“I ᐸ3 My Choppa” is a tale of gun violence in Tay-K’s hometown of Arlington, Texas.

Tay-K follows in the footsteps of classic Nas and 2Pac tracks in using personification to give his gun a personality of its own.

Tay’s affinity for violence has led to his arrest and indictment for capital murder charges in 2017.
